Surprising that so few values are 0 - this would seem to suggest that the bulk of students are immigrants, which seems unlikely.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##     0.0     2.0     6.0     6.5    10.0    16.0  452762

This may be a useless value, as there are so many NAs (98%). It’s possible that kids who were born in the country of the test simply did not fill this out because it seemed not applicable (that is, they never immigrated, so even 0 is not a logical answer). That said, one can also immagine that there may be a non-response bias here, where kids who are immigrants are reluctant to say so, so imputing a ‘0’ value for all NAs may be misguided. 

## Country of test   Other country            NA's 
##          441726           34637            9127

A good, low number of NAs (~1.9%). This may help make a case for imputing values for the immigration age variable.

UNIVARIATE ANALYSIS

Many of the distributions are normal, which is nice. Consider a strategy for imputing values across the immigration_age variable. Also, is the region code actually necessary? It may not be unless I’m going to compare regions, which may be very difficult if they’re not in the US. Check whether the States that have a different country value than the United States of America (Florida, Connecticut and Massachusetts) are already included in the US value and can be dropped, or if they should be aggregated into the US.

The scores from the tests have strong linear correlation. The variance for science scores given a math score appears smaller than the variance for reading scores given a math score. Given that Science is more math-based, this is not surprising.
